# HTML Linting and Validation

## Requirement

All HTML files SHALL be validated using the W3C HTML Validator before commits.

All HTML files SHALL pass W3C HTML5 validation without errors.

## W3C Validator

HTML files SHALL be validated using the W3C HTML Validator. The validator SHALL be run as part of the linting process defined in the Makefile.

## Validation Requirements

- All HTML files SHALL pass W3C validation with zero errors
- Warnings SHOULD be addressed but are not blocking
- Validation SHALL check for HTML5 compliance
- Validation SHALL check for proper tag nesting and structure
- Validation SHALL check for required attributes

## Local Validation

Developers SHALL run validation locally before committing changes. The `make lint` target SHALL run validation on all HTML files.

## Validation Tools

The W3C Validator can be used via:

1. Command-line tool (if available)
2. W3C Validator API
3. Online validator at https://validator.w3.org/

The Makefile SHALL integrate W3C validation into the linting process.

## Template Files

HTML files containing template engine syntax (Jinja2, Handlebars, etc.) MAY require special handling:

- Template blocks MAY be temporarily replaced with valid HTML before validation
- Validation SHOULD be performed on the rendered output when possible
- Template syntax within otherwise valid HTML structure is acceptable

## Pre-commit Validation

HTML validation SHALL be integrated into the development workflow. The `make lint` target SHALL be run before commits.

## Error Handling

When validation errors are found:

1. Errors SHALL be fixed before committing
2. Validation errors SHALL NOT be ignored or suppressed
3. If template syntax causes false positives, document the exception and validate the rendered output
